e":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ferrers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire (Eure) and Ferrières (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferris","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Ó Fearghuis</b> or <b>Ó Fearghasa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fearghus</i>’, or from the Scottish-Gaelic form of this personal name, <i>Fearghus</i> (see   Fergus  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure and Ferrières, La Manche in Normandy, France."]},{"name":"Ferridge","meanings":["English: unexplained; possibly a form of  <i>Ferris</i> and therefore a variant of   Ferrers  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh de Ferrers was born about 1176, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Walchelin de Ferriers, was 41 and his mother, Lady Alice de Lechelade, was 31. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Margaret de Saye."},"et":{"about 1176–":"umbes 1176–Surnud","1170–1211":"1170–1211","1172–Male":"1172–Surnud","1176–Male":"1176–Surnud","1177–1225":"1177–1225","1182–1242":"1182–1242","1206–Female":"1206–Surnud","1208–Male":"1208–Surnud","1136–1201":"1136–1201","1146–1210":"1146–1210","before 1166":"enne 1166","1242":"1242","1176":"1176","1172":"1172","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1206":"1206","1225":"1225","abt 1206":"umbes 1206","1136":"1136","1146":"1146","1201":"1201","1211":"1211","1210":"1210","1177":"1177","about 1176":"umbes 1176","1208":"1208","Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tutbury, Staffordshire, England":"Tutbury, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Winwick, Northamptonshire, England":"Winwick, Northamptonshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1176–":"noin 1176–Kuollut","1170–1211":"1170–1211","1172–Male":"1172–Kuollut","1176–Male":"1176–Kuollut","1177–1225":"1177–1225","1182–1242":"1182–1242","1206–Female":"1206–Kuollut","1208–Male":"1208–Kuollut","1136–1201":"1136–1201","1146–1210":"1146–1210","before 1166":"ennen vuotta 1166","1242":"1242","1176":"1176","1172":"1172","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1206":"1206","1225":"1225","abt 1206":"noin 1206","1136":"1136","1146":"1146","1201":"1201","1211":"1211","1210":"1